name: Etiuda Op. 10 Nr. 12
comments: "Étude Op. 10 Nr. 12 in C minor", known as the "Revolutionary Étude" or the "Étude on the Bombardment of Warsaw", is a solo piano work written circa 1831 and the last in Chopin's first set "Etudes Op.10" dedicated "à son ami Franz Liszt" ("to his friend Franz Liszt").

name: Etiuda Op. 25 Nr. 9
comments: "Étude Op. 25, No. 9 in G-flat major", known as the "Butterfly Étude", is an étude by Frédéric Chopin. The title "Butterfly" or "Le papillon" was not given by Chopin as is true for all Chopin pieces with such titles.

name: Etiuda Op. 10 Nr. 5
comments: "Étude Op. 10, No. 5 in G-flat major" is a study for solo piano composed in 1830. It was first published in 1833 in France, Germany and England as the fifth piece of Chopin's "Études Op. 10". This work is characterized by the rapid triplet figuration played by the right hand exclusively on black keys.

name: Consolation No. 3 in D-flat major
comments: The Consolations, S.172 are a set of six solo piano works by Franz Liszt. The third Consolation is in D-flat major and initially marked as "Lento placido". It is the most popular of the Consolations

name: Hungarian Rhapsody No. 10
comments: "Hungarian Rhapsody No. 10 in E major", S.244/10 is a composition for solo piano. It is the tenth in the set of Liszt's "Hungarian Rhapsodies" and is subtitled "Preludio" although this name is not commonly used. It was published in 1853 along with the rest of the first fifteen rhapsodies. The piece is one of the more popular Hungarian Rhapsodies.

name: Hungarian Rhapsody No. 12 in C
comments: "Hungarian Rhapsody No. 12 in C-sharp minor" (a.k.a. "No. 2") S.244/12, is the twelfth Hungarian Rhapsody by Franz Liszt.

name: Med sukker på
comments: Probably better known as "Vise for gærne jinter". The song has a somewhat complicated story. It was originally written as a poem in 1960, published in Arbeiderbladet that year. The same year, Bjørn Amdahl wrote the melody for the song. Prøysen recorded this for NRK (Norwegian radio) in 1963, but never released a version of the song himself. The melody was otherwise mostly unknown for the public, and when it was first published in "Alf Prøysens verker - Samlede viser og vers" the composer is written as "Unknown".  10th August 1968, the title "Vise for gærne jinter" appeared when lyrics were published again in Arbeiderbladet. Amdahl and Prøysen had a deal that no other composers could write a melody for the Prøysen songs that Amdahl composed, but since it apparently was an unknown composer, Egil Monn-Iversen wrote a melody for the song in 1974 for the play "Kjæm du i kveld".  This melody has become the standard version of the song, and the first version that was released on record, as an instrumental in 1979. A third melody was written by Per Hommelhaug.

name: Kom mai, du skjønne milde
comments: The Norwegian and Danish adaption of this song has been published in numerous song books for more than 150 years. The first Norwegian version was published in to different school song books in 1850: Ludvig Mathias Lindeman's "Tyve Sange for 2 Stemmer, Sopran og Alt, eller Tenor og Bas" og i Johan D. Behrens' "Skole-Sangbog indeholdende to- tre- og firestemmige Sange. Første Hefte, 40 tostemmige Sange for Sopran og Alt, eller Tenor og Bas 2". It is not known which of them were first. The song was published in two Danish school song books before that, the fifth nuber of A.P. Berggreen's "Sange til Skolebrug" (1844) and the Erslevs brothers' "Haandbog ved Sangunderviisningen i Skoler" (1845). Both of these had four stanzas of Overbeck's lyrics translated to Danish. Lindeman published a more or less unchanged Danish lyric, while Behrens translated some of the lines to Norwegian. Note that several older Norwegian song books credits the original German lyrics to Daniel Jäger, but this has been proven to be wrong.

name: Sønner av Norge
comments: Also known as "Norsk Nationalsang". The de facto national anthem of Norway from 1820 until the early 20th century. From the mid-1860s, "Ja, vi elsker dette landet" gradually came to occupy the unofficial position as national anthem, but was used alongside "Sønner av Norge" until the early 20th century, with "Sønner av Norge" being preferred in official situations. The anthem was written after Det Kongelige Selskap for Norges Vel had announced a competition to write a national anthem for Norway in 1819.

name: Norsk fædrelandssang [National Anthem of Norway]
comments: The original lyrics to the Norwegian national anthem ("Ja, vi elsker") was first printed in Aftenbladet in 1859. The poem was printed again in a re-written form in Illustreret Nyhedsblad in 1863. The final version, still used today, was printed in Bjørnson's "Digte og Sange"in 1870 with 8 verses and was then named "Ja, vi elsker". The melody for the poem was composed by Rikard Nordraak, Bjørnson's cousin, in 1863.

name: Ja, vi elsker [National Anthem of Norway]
comments: Bjørnson originally wrote the lyrics as a poem called "Norsk fædrelandssang" in 1859. It was later re-written for a publication in 1864, the year after it was put to melody by Bjørnson's cousin, Nordraak. Nordraak must then have written the melody for the original lyric. The final version of the lyrics, or poem, was published in Bjørnson "Sange og Digte" in 1870, and is the version use today. The song was printed by Behrens in 1864, and the same year first performed by 24 singers from the three largest male choirs in Kristiania (Oslo) 17th of May 1864 for the 50th anniversary of the Norwegian consistution day.

Tchaikovsky's setting is often known in English as "None but the Lonely Heart" and has been set in many vocal, choral and instrumental arrangements.

name: Nur wer die Sehnsucht kennt [poem]
comments: "Nur wer die Sehnsucht kennt" is derived from Goethe's 1795 second novel "Wilhelm Meisters Lehrjahre" (Wilhelm Meister's Apprenticeship). It is one of the songs of Mignon, a character in the novel. The poem has been set to music by many composers among them Beethoven, Schubert (six settings, the last two included in "Gesänge aus Wilhelm Meister" D 877), Schumann, Wolf and Tchaikovsky (via its translation into Russian by Lev Mei). Tchaikovsky's setting is often known in English as "None but the Lonely Heart" and has been set in many vocal, choral and instrumental arrangements.
